TY  - JOUR
AU  - Caselli, Francesco
AU  - Morelli, Massimo
AU  - Rohner, Dominic
T1  -  The Geography of Interstate Resource Wars *
PY  - 2015
Y1  - 2015/02/01
DO  - 10.1093/qje/qju038
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 130
IS  - 1
SP  - 267
EP  - 315
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  -  We establish a theoretical and empirical framework to assess the role of resource endowments and their geographic location in interstate conflict. The main predictions of the theory are that conflict is more likely when at least one country has natural resources, when the resources in the resource-endowed country are closer to the border, and, in the case where both countries have natural resources, when the resources are located asymmetrically vis-à-vis the border. We test these predictions on a novel data set featuring oilfield distances from bilateral borders. The empirical analysis shows that the presence and location of oil are significant and quantitatively important predictors of interstate conflicts after World War II. 
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/qje/qju038
ER  - 



